 negotiate Warden tolerance for three bells.\",\n        \"Convince a Salted Compact circle to accept a narrow ceasefire without losing face.\",\n        \"Post the agreed drum pattern for the ceasefire on the quay notice wall.\",\n        \"Ensure one relief barge passes safely during the ceasefire window.\"\n      ],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Jalen Sarq\", \"lines\": \"You smell like mothwax and court brass today, and yet here you are where the ropes bite and the canal listens for truth in footsteps. I am not asking you to love me or to forgive sootglass; I am asking you to remember the way a child looks when the shops shutter for a week and the bread turns to rumor. Three bells of quiet, that is all I am buying and all I am selling, and in those bells the Veil will sheath its teeth and keep its warm hands in its pockets. The Compact will move grain on agreed routes and no black ledgers will slide across the Exchange tables while the moon stares. The Wardens can glare from their towers and polish their harness as if mercy were a regulation, and afterward we can all go back to pretending we do not live off each other’s breath. I trust you because you hate famine more than fines, and because when the water takes a man you do not ask which guild signed his last wage before you lean out with the hook. So come, Kade Orrel, take these terms in your fist like a line in wind, and we will see if this city prefers bread to bravado.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Aren Mir\", \"lines\": \"I taught you to tie a boarding line in a gale and I still see your hands in the knot, steady as a drum-beat and twice as true. You come asking me to look away while masks run ferries in fog, and you know I have pulled too many bodies from water that claimed to be honest. My duty is a dull blade, Kade, but it cuts every day and it cuts me too when I have to choose between law and a mother’s pantry. Give me something to trust, and not a wish or a whisper, but a pattern I can point to when the Captain asks why my men did not jump. I want a whistle code, a drumline drawn clean, and a face at the bow who can stand a lantern without flinching, and then I will tell the wind to use its inside voice for three bells. If you cross me, I will not hang you, but I will make you carry the rope back to the memorial and add your own knot for the trust you broke.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Kade Orrel\", \"lines\": \"I did not come to polish anyone’s conscience, and I did not bring lace for the law or perfume for the Veil. I came because the quays feed the city before the bells do, and because a hungry city makes its own monsters faster than any syndicate or court. Here is the pattern, stamped in my head and written in chalk for those who need eyes more than ears, and here are the names of the pilots on the relief barge with the marks they carry on their wrists. If a masked hand touches a tiller during those three bells I will break that hand myself and tie it to the notice wall with the rope it tried to steal, and I will write that lesson in ash big enough for the moon to read. I will walk the quay while the drums speak, and I will stand on the bow when the barge noses out, and if the river tries to tell a different story I will argue it down with steel and cord. We do this clean, and afterward we can go back to arguing about which pocket pays for the next dawn.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Cord-Master Tavin Greel\", \"lines\": \"We measure worth in Molden by who holds the rope when the knot turns, and by how many fingers a man keeps after the gates finish their sermon. My pilots will not run blind again and they will not carry blame for deaths minted by other people’s schedules, not while I can still smell a storm half a day ahead. A safety steward in every Engine shift-room remains our demand, even during a truce, and a narrow ceasefire cannot be a muzzle that makes us eat our own pride. But if the pattern you bring is honest, and if the Wardens 