epeat the whistle code after you, and you make them look at the names of the relief barge pilots as if names were knots that hold. You end by placing a buoy-stone on the pattern to bear witness, and you refuse to move until someone else adds weight. When the wind shifts, it feels like a gate opening somewhere in the city’s throat.\", \"outcome\": \"The Wardens agree to stand at a respectful distance, and Aren Mir signs the moment with a nod that will count at Windward Bastion even if no paper does. The Salted Compact accepts the narrow ceasefire without losing face, because it was won aloud and in front of their dead rope, and the pilots tap the buoy-stone like a pledge. The relief barge passes under a watch of eyes instead of blades, and the river pretends it always intended to be gentle, and for once the Aur is believed. Jalen Sarq keeps the Veil quiet because the crowd would have noticed any slip, and his gratitude comes in the form of silence that stays bought. You gain the goodwill promised by the Compact, a leniency marker from Aren Mir, and a truce token from the Veil without hidden stains, and word spreads that you can braid rivals into a single rope long enough to cross a hard span.\"},\n        {\"id\": \"C2\", \"title\": \"Quiet Knots with the Veil\", \"text\": \"You take Jalen aside into the underquay’s peeled shadow where the stone sweats and the river speaks in secret syllables, and you bargain like a pilot counting fathoms by touch. You promise him a clean window if he swears on the Ashmask Warrens that not a single ingot or black ledger will cross during the three bells, and you tell him you will break any hand that tries. You convince him to place two of his own to watch the watchers, not to threaten but to shame, because a man watched by his kin handles a tiller more carefully. You then carry the promise to Aren, asking for tolerance phrased as a drill exercise, and you let him believe that making allowance is itself an act of discipline. You keep 